    content: "What are we?\n\nPerhaps, an ever-evolving species forwarding into absolute chaos.\n\nWho are we?\n\nMaybe, a bunch of conscious beings flying around in space-time, aiming to understand the world around us.\n\nWhere are we?\n\nOn a formation of fundamental particles based on fundamental forces, that are manifesting reality as we know it.\n\nWhen are we?\n\nTime, a mere visualization aiding us through our existential journey.\n\nWhy do we exist?\n\nA goalless civilization surviving, later to be faced by ultimate extinction.\n\nWhat brought us here?\n\nAn evolutionary journey that went through the course of the years, leading to this moderately intelligent species.\n\nis there a point of it all?\n\nNo probably, but yet, we exist here on this floating sphere-like object, around our source of energy, with critical and detailed conditions leading to our prosperity.\n\nBut is it that detailed?Are we on our own?\n\nwhat exists in the great beyond?\n\nwhy, how, and when?\n\nquestions wandering around, seeking answers.\n\nBut are they answerable?Answers are easier than questions, for the latter is infinite.\n\nBut after all, what is anything?\n\nwhat does it mean to be here, and why?\n\nare we really the leftovers of a long sequence of evolutionary mechanisms, that by chance, existed?\n\nOr are we living upon a grand design along a designer?\n\nSomeone who purposefully simulated this rock, and allowed the very first bacteria to develop and evolve as he nurtured all necessary conditions.\n\nBut why?\n\nWhat ishe?\n\nWhere?\n\nWhen?\n\nAn answer to raise more questions, but after all, questions are the fuel of science.\n\nThe universe is built upon fundamental laws, that if broken, would lead to complete chaos.\n\nthat level of accuracy leads to confusion.\n\nWhether it’s Hubble’s constant, the universal gravitational constant or even the very mass of fundamental particles.\n\nAny of the mentioned, if tuned to a different value would lead to a chaotic.\n\nNevertheless, this seems like a biased example.To begin, many tend to compare the ”perfectionism” of earth and use it to aid the argument as to God simulated this earth for us all.\n\nHowever, with the recent discoveries of many exo-planets that may sustain life, this argument is easily refuted.\n\nReports of 2020 already identify 24 exoplanets having the super ability to sustain life.\n\nAnother study suggests that the number of earth-like planets is around 6 billion in our galaxy only.\n\nAll of the preceding argument follows the earth uniqueness, not the universe’s.Above, I mentioned the detailed accuracy of our universe, and how a slight difference in any of the constants could have led to the universe collapsing on itself.\n\nSimilar to the ”earth and its twins” refutation, manyphysiciststend to use the multiverse argument, as to say that billions of universes co-exist, and that disproves the uniqueness of our universe.I’ll state my opinion of the wholemultiverse fantasylater through this blog, but now, lets just say that its closer to being anavengers related theme, rather than real science.\n\nHowever, we should tackle each argument at a time.\n\nConsidering the earth-universe uniqueness:As mentioned earlier, the refutation of the earth uniqueness is direct and supported with experimental proof.\n\nIn 2009, the Kepler space telescope was launched having only one mission: detect the presence of earth-like worlds.\n\nThe telescope used the transit method in order to detect the presence of a planet, and through the initial data received, researchers were able to derive other data such as density (the latter determines the nature of the planet) and mass of it…et ceteraOther methods are used, including one that detects and calculates the gravitational effects of a planet on its host star, and similarly, data can be derived of it.\n\nConsidering the universe uniqueness, we can’t really judge how unique our universe is, since we don’t have any other samples to compare.\n\nIt’s like seeing an apple in an empty fridge, and saying that an apple is a very unique fruit.\n\nOn the other hand, assuming that there exists an infinite kinds of fruits which we can’t interact with is not much of a solution.\n\nWith the absence of a real experimental proof of another sample (another universe), we can’t really judge whether our universe is unique or not.\n\nHowever, one might argue that there exists a possibility of our universe being the only universe, in that, the universe is surely unique and requires a simulator.\n\nWe don’t have any experimental proof on that, and the way I see it, we won’t any time soon.\n\nNo, I’m not revolving around the question, I’ll come to answer it.\n\nThrough the possibility that we come to witness the proof of only one universe, It won’t disprove the existence of other universes: One might argue that maybe through time, many universes popped in and out of existence, and our observations doesn’t cover all times, thus, we need more precise observations, and our theory of one universe reflects a one-sided truth.Summarizing, the earth-universe uniqueness is not a proof on the existence of a deity: a grand designer that simulated earth and allowed the prosperity of us humans.\n\nConsidering the survival of species:\n\nWe existed for millions of years, us humans, and many other species, going through the a never-ending evolution.\n\nLife evolved here on planet earth, from plants to flying creatures, and going deep to the wide oceans.\n\nLife thrived everywhere.\n\nIt would be completely ironic to assume that life in unique, considering its wide existence here.When we are aiming to detect life forms out of our lovely dot, we tend to focus our eyes on worlds existing in the habitable zone, the latter allows the existence of liquid water on the planet’s surface.\n\nBut life may thrive on different conditions.\n\nSurely we won’t go on a blind quest seeking a life form that exists on radiation given the fact that we don’t know whether it exists or not.\n\nAll I’m saying is that lifemayexist at such conditions.\n\nThis wide existence and ability of life to adapt and exist at different conditions proves the non-uniqueness of it.\n\nThe Mariana Trench, deepest point on earth, holds a wide variety of creatures that adapted to the absence of light.\n\nYes, life is flexible, adaptive and self-evolving, thus, it has no worth mentioning uniqueness.\n\nSummarizing, the universe-earth-life uniqueness is easily refuted, if God is all perfect and omni, I believe he should’ve created a more detailed universe, one less chaotic maybe. I know what you’re thinking: Who am I to tell God what to do? After all, he is omni, or isn’t he?\n\nThroughout the rise of any civilization, god(s) took a piece out of the cake.\n\nThe Greeks went to the extreme, assigning gods to any un-explainable phenomena.\n\nFor example, cupid, the god of love in roman mythology, used to pierce the hearts of humans with his golden arrows, thus causing them to fall in love.\n\nNevertheless, now science can tell us about the chemistry of love, and how it’s all related to hormones jumping around in our brains.\n\nThe heart had nothing to do with it cupid, you misaimed.But is that only how God exists?\n\na thought about an un-explainable phenomena that will come to be explained later, and thus the illusion of a god evaporates with it?\n\nwell, we first need to know what makes god, god.There exists around 4300 religions, each with a god, and a set of rules, and a story.\n\nThus, I’ll skip this mess of trying to grasp nearly 4000 gods in one blog, and I’ll skip the religion dilemma: Here, I’m talking of an omni-god, a god that only he exists, and can exist, and a god that cannot be matched.\n\nThe god I will be trying to explain is un-explainable, because he’s out of reach and perfect, and he’s surely an omni-god.The omni-god:The idea of an omnipotent god is recorded to be side by side with the emergence of the Abrahamic religions.\n\nBut what does it mean to be omnipotent?\n\nI mean, what makes god, god?\n\nHis own characteristics maybe.Why should a god be an omni one?\n\nIf god is not omni, thus he can be reached and matched in a finite interval of time, which makes him unworthy of the term god.\n\nBut can an omni-god exist?\n\nAn omni-god is often met with several paradoxes, such as the rock paradox: stating that if god could create a rock that he cannot move, then he’s not strong (since he can’t move it), and if he couldn’t create that, then he’s not capable enough.\n\nAlthough easily refuted by saying that the question itself makes no sense because it comes head to head with god’s own perfection, many philosophers used this question as a proof on god’s short hand.I like generalizing the question by simply asking: Can god create a law he can’t break?\n\nAn omni-god though, is above all laws and questions.\n\nHe’s perfection itself, existing everywhere and every time.\n\nActually, he surpasses time and space.\n\nThis gets us with another paradox:If god exists at every time and at every place, he surely knows what he will do, and what he will create, thus, he doesn’t have power over his future self, making him uncapable.\n\nThe other way around is stating that in the above case, god is uncapable because of himself, thus, nothing other than him could put out barriers in front of his abilities, thus, he remains omnipotent.An omnipotent god is independent of any needs, he’s separated from any materialism, one with extreme abilities, so, our existence is not a necessity surely, or is it (Vsauce music intensifies).\n\nGod’s shortage?\n\nThe existence of a god is connected directly to his omnipotence.\n\nIf he’s not omnipotent, he isn’t god, because he’s reachable (already discussed)But what about us?\n\nNo apparent reason for our existence and yet we exist.\n\nGod could’ve remained on his own, without any of us, but we exist.\n\nIt’s either he decided to create us for a certain purpose he only knows, or our existence was obligatory on the omni one.This puts us in another paradox.\n\nIf God was obliged to create us, he isn’t omni, but if he wasn’t, why are we here?\n\nAnother question surrounded by fog usually answered by”heknow why, and it’s better if we don’t”.\n\nClearly this answer isn’t a satisfying one for a skeptic mind.On the other hand, is existence relative?\n\nNo.\n\nThe fall of a tree on its own with no sound heard, doesn’t mean the tree doesn’t exist.\n\nTo us, maybe, but, to itself, it surely exists.God is separated from all needs, thus, he doesn’t require to be known, because to him, it’s already a set table: If he knows he’s there, he doesn’t need anyone to know he’s there.The existence of omni-god suggests the existence of all fairytales creatures (even if theoretically only).\n\nIt advocates for the existence of a metaphysical world.\n\nGod being omnipotent makes him capable of creating everything and anything, even a flying elephant, or a unicorn.\n\nThus, the belief of such god’s existence obliges the belief of the impossible, things that surpass our imagination.\n\nIf god exists, he won’t follow up with our reasoning and logic, thus, our laws and even imagination, fall into this dark abyss.\n\nThe belief of god obliges the belief of imaginary creatures.\n\nI’ll leave you, my science scholars, to be the judge of that.Side note: I’d love to pet a dragon, so let’s ”pray” this is real.The imperfection of our world:\n\nA world full of hunger, disasters, and re-occurring wars through the course of history, is surely not a perfect one.\n\nSurely the above dilemma is refuted by religious figures, saying that our lives are tests, and a test should include problems, ones that we should go on a cruise to solve.\n\nAdd to that, one might argue that these evils aren’t god-made, as he, god, set us in neutral positions, for us to choose our own path.\n\nIn that, some civilizations chose this evil path, that included wars and hunger, while others chose a good path that included prosperity..et ceteraI find this refutation ironic in two approaches:First, If he god didn’t make these evils, and thus he doesn’t feel responsible of fixing them, then what’s the point of his existence as a supervisor?\n\nIs he a deistic god?\n\n(I’ll speak of the latter later)Secondly, The test refutation is really odd and holds a lot of questioning.\n\nWhy would god do a test on beings he created and then judge them?\n\nWhy didn’t god choose a test less brutal?\n\nTo that I add, given god is an omni one, he can create anything and everything, so he had the ability to create a test for us humans (for only him knows the reason) without this whole brutality and deaths.\n\nIs that the best, an omni god can create?\n\none might argue.\n\nSome might argue that god sent a set of rules, through religion, for us to follow and reach the safe shores, and in that, he helped and aided us.\n\nBut with the foundations of more than 4000 religions, I find this quite confusing.The existence of god was followed by the existence of religion: a group of rules set by the divine one, to aid humans in their survival journey on earth.To note, I don’t see any real connection between god and religion, and I find them both completely different topics, as I prefer to discuss godphilosophicallyandscientifically, while religion, is after all religion, based onbelief.\n\nWithin each civilization, religion was a basic component used as a connection with the gods.\n\nAs mentioned earlier, humans assigned gods to unknown phenomenon, and worshipped these gods through religion.\n\nThe latter is made of rules assigned to the human-human interactions, human-god interactions, and through some civilizations, god-god interactions.\n\nReligion is based on belief, as mentioned by all the books assigned to any religion, whether it’s buddhism, islam, christianity, or jewism…et ceteraSo, to skip the mess, I won’t attempt to prove any of the above logically or scientifically.\n\nMany of the rules don’t make sense, for me at least.\n\nNevertheless, it’s a belief, so if you believe that the omni-god sent this book with these rules for us humans, I can’t argue with you because you’ll usually start your argument by saying”Ibelieve”, while I’ll say”I know and I can prove”.\n\nThis, I know, is the difference between a scientist and a religious being.\n\nNo, I don’t mean to offend you, my dear religious scholars, I’m just stating the obvious fact mentioned in all religious books: A religion-based god is a god based on the belief in the books.This surely reminds me of the multiverse religion.\n\nOddly, most science scholars advocating for the multiverse hype arenon-believers.\n\nTo that, I shall mention RichardBefore summing-up, I won’t discuss the make-up of religion, or whether it’s man-made or godly.\n\nOn that, I prefer to discuss the idea of an omni-god.\n\nI think that I already mentioned the necessity of god being omnipotent, if he exists.\n\nI also mentioned the paradoxes derived by this assumption.\n\nAdd to that, the approaches taken to avoid these paradoxes.Summing-up on religion now, it cannot and will not be logically proven.\n\nIt’s a belief system, so, if you lack the curiosity to ask and wonder and derive rules of life, you can accept religion as a law, but, you cannot, and you are not assigned to oblige these rules on anyone.\n\nIf your religion talks of a god that wants everyone to believe in him, or else, hell shall be on people, then, I don’t think this god is much of an omni one, but more of a needy being for satisfaction, and although I’m not familiar with most religions, I doubt anyone asserts for such behavior.\n\nMany are the scholars believing in the existence of a grand designer, even more surprising, some of them tend to be religious.\n\nThis, on its own, is enough to end the whole propaganda made considering”Science is always trying to prove the inexistence of god”.\n\nBut, why such propaganda exists?To begin, we should understand what science is, and how science works, thus, we need to dig deep through the scientific method.\n\nThe scientific method:\n\nDating back to as far as Aristotle, the scientific method is considered a main building block in any theory.\n\nActually, any theory not following the scientific method, is considered biased and false.It goes like something like this:question –> research –> hypothesize –> experiment –> analyze –> conclude-1-Clearly, this differs from thereligious method, which goes something like this:question —> read the book —> believe —> do-2-\n\nUsually this difference is refuted by saying that religion is more into thewhyquestion, while science is always seeking thehowone.How did the universe come into existence?\n\nwhy did the universe come into existence?The former question is usually answered by making observations, calculations, and experiments.\n\nBut the latter goes deep into philosophy, and the way I see it, there goes two approaches.Approach one:If we assume that god doesn’t exist, and that the universe just happened to be by that mere moment of harmony between constants and values which also happened to be there, then asking why the universe existed doesn’t make sense, because there was absolutely no reason for it, thus asking this is like searching for a needle that doesn’t exist, in a big pile of wheat.\n\nIt’s a useless journey.Approach two:if we assume that god exists, and that he simulated the universe, and that he is an omni-god surely, then he is purposeful, and thus, a reason does exist for this simulation, then, this search is a fruitful one, and by that, we are seeking to understand god’s logic.Now, science is surely interested in the why question, even if many disagree.Let’s go back to the apple:That apple existing in the fridge on its own,whyis it there?\n\nI can answer by saying because I want to eat it.\n\nClearly that’s not a satisfying answer, because it didn’t tell ushowthe apple got here, bringing us back at the starting point: how did the apple get here?\n\nI put it there.As one can observe, the how-why questions are but representatives of each other.\n\nBut here, we are talking of the universe, not an apple.Caseone:Why does the universe exist?\n\nGod simulated it.\n\nHow did the universe come into existence?\n\nGod simulated it by these constants and values…et ceteraCase two:Why does the universe exist?\n\nIt’s just there, no apparent reason or purpose of it.\n\nHow did it exist?\n\nThe following constants and values went into harmony and caused this universe to exist.To sum-up, whether a scientist is religious or not, and whether he/she believes in god or not, the approach taken would be the same.\n\nIn science, we are not interested in”why did god decide to simulate the universe”.\n\nWe are interested in”why did the universe exist”,more precisely,how.The neutral science:Science is neither with, nor against religion.\n\nIf you’re a scientist seeking to prove god wrong, that’s your own journey, it surely doesn’t represent science as a whole.\n\nScience is actually not interested in god, whether he exists or he doesn’t.\n\nThe proof of his existence or inexistence won’t change the scientific method, and it surely won’t change the value of the Planck’s constant.\n\nScience is neutral, interested in the facts, in observations that reflect truth, not belief.\n\nI do respect all beliefs, and one should surely believe in something, his humanity even, thus, we, the science scholars are not in a fight with god, we are as neutral from him, as he from us.Now, I won’t go and blame Michio kaku for tweeting”the god equation”, and I won’t blame the media on the”god particle found”heading when the higgs boson was observed, or Richard Dawkins’scrazy obsessionwith the bearded man, but, I think it’s fair to say that some scientists are misusing their knowledge.\n\nDay by day, science passes new obstacles, and uncovers new horizons for us to visit, revealing the hidden lands of our wild universe.In the ancient times, the rains were nothing but gifts of the gods, now however, we can know when thegiftswill arrive, and how they do.\n\nThe eclipse was a demon swallowing the moon, and people would pray for the gods to kick this demon away.\n\nNow, we are able to detect thisdemon, and calculate its occurrence for years ahead.Science is clearly the light in the dark tunnel of life, but, the ending seems blurred.Death, remains god related.\n\nThrough the pharaohs, and reaching our current times, death remains a stuck block, strengthening the god argument intohisside.\n\nLife and its end, the necessity of death, and what comes later.\n\nIs it the end of our conscious beings, as we enter the ultimate void?\n\nor maybe it’s a new beginning within a new realm and level of consciousness.\n\nBut, what is consciousness?\n\nWhat does it mean to exist and to question?\n\nHow did this bacterium evolve to reach this ultimate prosperity?\n\nMore questions to answer.If we are able to answer the ultimate question of”what comes after death?”, I think we’d be steps away from ending the god discussion.\n\nIf he exists, surely something is on the other end, the omni-god is again a purposeful one, and having the evolution of a civilization for billions of years with no apparent reason doesn’t seem much purposeful.Clearly science is in a journey, to uncover the other side, and with nohintsfrom him existing, we are on our own, do it’s either us or time.\n\nGod doesn’t represent religion, and religion doesn’t represent god.\n\nBoth are different topics, studied differently.\n\nGod is philosophical, while religion is theological.To us, physicists (I’m a mini-physicist so yes), the existence of god won’t matter a lot, no particles would change, no forces would be affected.\n\nThe universe is the way is it, and we already know a lot of it, but we are digging deeper, into its very foundations.\n\nMaybe he exists, and then, I’ll surely be thankful because he gave me this chance of living and observing all this beauty, the lights, the stars, all are magnificent.\n\nAnd I’ll surely have a long discussion withhim.\n\nIf he doesn’t, then, I shall thank coincidence maybe, that gave me these days to change the world, and to love and to share my experiences, in this very interval of time.\n\nOur existence is a miracle, with or without god’s existence.So no, I won’t end my blog like Collin Wilson ended his book by turning the light on and sleeping in fear of god (which he refuted in his book).\n\nI also won’t be scared of the lightening like Richard Dawkins and Steven Weinberg did when they were discussing him (I know they were sarcastic so save the comment).\n\nI’ll end by saying that if such god exists, I’m pretty sure that he doesn’t mind my questions, and my ability to explain him, and I think he’d love answering my questions one day (if he exists).\n\nI think that if such god exists, he’d be democratic, loving to discuss, and a good god, since he’s omni.As of my ultimate question, it’d bewhy.\n\nWhy did you create anything god?\n\nyou are omnipotent, you could’ve spent eternity on your own, and you wouldn’t have felt a difference with or without our existence.\n\nWhy humans exactly?\n\nwhy this shape and why this world?\n\nYou had the ability to create a completely differently looking race, with different thoughts and minds.\n\nWhy us?\n\nIn that, I want to know what’s so special about these fighting moderately intelligent species.\n\nClearly, the past few decades science made huge discoveries, which had one negative effect on the science community: The dawn of the atheistic multiverse religion.It is ironic, that Richard Dawkins, a great biologist and Nobel laureate, he who always denies god and religion, goes and supports the multiverse.To you, my dear Sir Dawkins, the multiverse doesn’t differ much from religion, it’s based on belief.You can simply assume the existence of billions of universes, but you cannot prove them, you cannot observe them (currently at least), and they won’t affect our observations of our universe.\n\nThey won’t help in developing any of the current theories.\n\nAnother ironic behavior of this atheistic religion is spotted in the beginning of the book”the god delusion”, by Richard Dawkins (once again).\n\nHe begins with inviting you to atheism as if he’s pretty sure of its righteousness, which is similar to the behavior taken by religious parties.\n\nI didn’t like the book (as you concluded I guess), and although in chapter 3, Richard tries to differentiate between atheism and religion, he wasn’t that effective.I was disappointed with the book actually, given the title, I thought it would go more into god rather than religion.\n\nSame goes with”God is not great”by Christopher Hitchkens.\n\nI think both Hitchkens and Dawkins need to rename their books as”the religion delusion”and”religion is not great”.In the end, it’s one man’s thought of a book.\n\nSadly, the book is taken by most atheists as a reference, similar to the quran in islam, or the bible in christianity.\n\nClearly atheists are turning into this religious behavior, while holding science as the saving sign.\n\nSo to sum-up, science doesn’t represent atheism, and atheism doesn’t represent science.Many scholars I know are religious, and many Nobel laureates were, so clearly no logical conclusion can be made.Summing up, although the omni god assumption arises a lot of paradoxes, the bearded man cannot exist if he’s not all powerful.\n\nAdd to that, him being omnipotent allows him to defy our logic and thus answer these paradoxes.\n\nI end with my last assumption:The omni god is irrefutable, thus, once we assume his existence, we cannot assume the opposite, because his omnipotence answers all the questions.\n- Is god’s omnipotence obligatory on him? in that, doesn’t he become uncapable over his own characteristics?\n- Can god grow and become better? Or is he the best, thus he cannot reach for higher levels, because he’s already on top of all?\n- Can god create something better than the best thing he ever created?\n- Is religion a necessity of life?\n- Can ourcurrentworld prosper with no god or religion? Answer as a realist."
